The Grail Records

Guide

University of Notre Dame Archives

2019

Creator: Grail (Organization)
Title: The Grail Records
Dates: 1921-2015.
Extent: 300 linear feet
Language: English.
Identification: GRL

Background

The Grail is an international women's movement committed to spiritual search, social transformation, global solidarity, ecological sustainability, and the release of women's creative energy throughout the world -- bonded in action, solidarity, and faith, working in 17 countries, as individuals and Grail groups, interconnecting regionally, nationally and internationally. (Source: The Grail US website. See http://www.grail-us.org)

Return to the Table of Contents

Scope and Content

Documents dating circa 1921 to circa 1993, divided into five general categories: International, National, Grailville, Special Projects, and Publications; including lectures presented by Grail founder, Jacques van Ginneken, S.J., and international and U.S. Grail leaders; correspondence and program material from Grail teams and centers located in Africa, Asia, Australia, Canada, the Caribbean, Latin American, Europe, and the Middle East; program material from U.S. city centers and three major U.S. residential centers (Loveland, OH, Cornwall-on-Hudson, NY, and San Jose, CA); reflections on the purpose and goals of a group of celibate members known as the “nucleus”; magazines, books, and pamphlets published by the Grail, documenting contributions to the lay apostolate, the role of women, liturgical renewal, ecumenism, and rural life; documentation of the changes from exclusively Roman Catholic membership to inclusion of women from other faiths and from a hierarchical to lateral structures; documentation of para-liturgies, dramas, songs, and celebratory rituals; and documentation of a progressive development towards feminist theology and feminist undergraduate and graduate education.

This is a preliminary inventory, based on finding aids or packing lists sent by the donor. Gaps in numbering generally correspond to boxes that have not yet been sent.

CGRL The Grail : Manuscripts

CGRL 1-15/ INTERNATIONAL FILES

CGRL 1/ REV. JACQUES VAN GINNEKEN, S.J.

This series is divided into four major subseries: Talks / Lectures, Travel Letters, Articles and Miscellaneous.

CGRL 1/ Talks / Lectures

This subseries is composed of three major categories: 1) Retreat talks, 2) the "Woman" Course, and 3) Miscellaneous. The first category is made up of the transcribed retreat talks Fr. Van Ginneken gave for the Grail members at de Tiltenberg (the International Grail Center in Holland). It consists of 32 separate speeches and meditations. The "Woman" Course was presented, to the Grail members, less than a month after the retreat. The course also consisted of 32 lectures and dealt with the psychology of women. This course became the common base upon which the Grail and formation of new members was based. This course is incomplete, as of October 1984 lectures #27-29 are still missing. The Miscellaneous section consists of various speeches and lectures by Fr. van Ginneken. These talks are not tied as closely together as the retreat or course lectures but instead deal with a different aspect which early Grail leaders felt were essential for the development of members. All three sections contain the Dutch version and usually one or more English translations. The material is arranged numerically and chronologically by category.

CGRL 1/ Travel Letters

This subseries consists of letters written by Rev. van Ginneken, to the Grail, as he traveled through Europe (primarily the Alps). They were meant primarily to be a type of meditation for the nucleus members and in fact numerous excerpts are included as used by the Grail. The letters are in Dutch with one or more English translations. The material is arranged numerically.

CGRL 1/ Articles

Written works by or about van Ginneken which may have been given as talks or lectures. Articles in Dutch, French and English. Records arranged chronologically.

CGRL 1/ Miscellaneous

Various material related to van Ginneken's work. Although probably not written by him, the material appears to draw heavily upon his work extensively. Also included is a sample of Fr. Van Ginneken's handwriting. Material is in both Dutch and English. Records arranged chronologically.

CGRL 2/ INTERNATIONAL STRUCTURES

This diverse series is a collection of the changing statutes, rules, charters and structures of the Grail dating from their early beginnings as the Women of Nazareth to more recent adaptations. It consists of working drafts, census replies, suggestions and evaluations by Grail members, background reference material and the finished drafts. From 1965 most material relating to change or revisions of the statutes centers around the International General Assembly, which acts as the policy making and direction setting body of the Grail. This series also contains some material on the International Nucleus Statutes both alone and as a part of the general statutes. Also of interest is a collection of prints of the early insignia of the Women of Nazareth. See also "International General Assembly," "National Committee" and "International Meetings" Series for additional background material and "Books" Series for additional bound copies of the finished product. This series is arranged chronologically.

Material is subdivided into individual IGA's and arranged chronologically by year of the Assembly.

CGRL 4/ INTERNATIONAL GENERAL MEETINGS

This series is composed of material dealing with meetings and issues of International Grail concern and contains correspondence, minutes, worksheets, reports and research material as well as questionnaires and responses. Most International Meetings consist of a single folder which has one or more of the above types of records contained, with the exception of the Aggiornamento Year which has several folders divided into record types.

For additional information see also: "International General Assembly" and "International Structures" Series.

Material arranged chronologically by date of the meeting, then numerically or chronologically within the folder. The Questionnaires, however, are grouped by question and type of response.

CGRL 5/ INTERNATIONAL SECRETARIATE

This series is made up of correspondence including general correspondence and letters from the International President to the National President. Most of the early general correspondence is in Dutch and from "Mother Margaret," the first International Grail President. Of special interest is one hand-written note from Rev. van Ginneken penciled in on the back of a letter from Holland. Also in this series are scattered files on the elections of the International President and Vice-Presidents, financial records, miscellaneous reports, address lists, and subject files which deal in large part with Grail - United Nations relations under UNESCO, UFER, and NGO. The correspondence is arranged chronologically, the elections are divided into Presidential or Vice-Presidential and arranged chronologically within each section. The Subject files are arranged alphabetically by subject and chronologically within each. All other record types are arranged chronologically.

CGRL 8-15/ MATERIAL ON OTHER COUNTRIES

This series consists of major subseries: Missions, Africa, Asia, Australia, Canada, Caribbean, Europe, and Latin America. Each subseries is further divided into countries, regions or cities and within these by record type. Material is filed under the name of the country at the time the material was produced so there may be material on the same center under two different country names. Most material is in English, but the early material especially is in Dutch, German or French. The material contained is as diverse as the continents, countries and cities represented. Included are reports, correspondence, reference material, course and program material (lecture outlines, training aids, pamphlets, etc.) flyers, reprints of dramas presented, newspaper clippings, and subject files. Some areas of interest include reports written by Dutch Grail members in Holland at the time of Nazi occupation and the files dealing with the revolutions in Africa and Latin America. The file on England is also of special interest as the correspondence contains details of the English Grail's wartime activity. Although the English Grail still exists today, it is in name only. It is no longer a member of the International Grail having severed ties in the late 1940s.

The material within the series is arranged alphabetically by continent, region, country or city, then by record type and chronologically within each record type.

CGRL 16-62/ NATIONAL FILES (US)

CGRL 16-17/ NATIONAL GENERAL ASSEMBLY (US)

Correspondence; reference files; agendas, both typed and handwritten; minutes; financial records; reports; working papers; evaluations; address lists; regional meetings, held in relation to upcoming General Assemblies, files; and miscellaneous material dealing with individual General Assemblies. Only scant records remain from the 1969 and 1978 General Assemblies, but the 1975 General Assembly is well documented. Most of the records are typed rather than hand written, including the correspondence which in most instances is just form letters.

Of special interest are the 1969 General Assembly which dealt with the question of Protestant participation and the 1975 General Assembly which dealt with the possibility of Jewish participation in the Grail. The unit, as a whole, details not only what was dealt with at individual General Assemblies, but what individual Grail members felt would be dealt with.

The material is divided into individual General Assemblies and arranged chronologically by the year of the assembly. The material is then subdivided within each assembly by record type and arranged chronologically, with the exception of the "Evaluations" and "Regional Meetings" series which are first arranged alphabetically.

CGRL 18/ TASK FORCES

Material from the three national Task Forces: Liberation Task Force, Religious Search Task Force and Women's Task Force. Included are program files, reports, resource material, address lists, evaluations, questionnaires, correspondence and miscellaneous material. By far the largest part of this unit is the program file, which describes and delineates different programs, sponsored, co-sponsored or attended by the members of the individual Task Forces. It should be noted that the Task Forces often helped set and carry on the goals of the Grail as decided in the General Assembly. In fact, the 1971 International General Assembly also established this structure and areas of concern to help delineate the goals and interest areas of the International Grail.

The material is divided into individual Task Forces which are arranged alphabetically by the Task Force name. Within each Task Force the material is divided by record type and then within each record type either chronologically or alphabetically as with the program files.

CGRL 19/ NATIONAL CONFERENCE 1962-1966

The National Conference (national meeting) material consists of correspondence (a large percentage being form letters), financial reports, participants and address lists, resource material (readings to help prepare for issues to be discussed at the conferences), transcribed talks given at the conference (only in 1962 and 1964), agendas, minutes, reports, working papers and miscellaneous material.

Conferences of special interest include the 1962 conference which discussed "Woman's place in the church and the world" and the 1964 and 1965 conferences which dealt with the aggiornamento process in the Catholic Church as a whole and within the Grail movement in particular. The National Conferences stopped in 1966 when their function was completely taken over by the General Assemblies. See also National Board Meetings and National Movement Records for additional information.

The material is divided by conference and arranged chronologically by year of conference. Within each conference the material is subdivided into record type and arranged chronologically within each type.

CGRL 19/ NATIONAL ADVISORY BOARD

The National Advisory Board material encompasses several different groups which were either closely related to the National Advisory Board by function and purpose or were eventually absorbed into the Board. Included in this classification is the national committee, the coordinators and the national staff.

The National Advisory Board contains some very diverse material. There is a small correspondence file which is mainly correspondence with then International Grail President, Rachel Donders, and one report covering Rachel's visit to the U.S. and Grailville in 1959. The bulk of the material is found in the "meetings" files, which contain agendas, minutes, working papers, correspondence, reference material, committee and project reports all filed together under a single meeting date. In the early 1960s the meetings centered around a certain theme, problem or goal. Later meetings were general, multi-topic meetings. Of special interest are the April and November 1961 National Advisory Board meetings in which members write about their early formation period in the Grail. See also National Conference and Elections for additional material.

Material is arranged first by original group name: National Advisory Board (National Board), National Committee, Coordinators, and National Staff. Within each group the material is subdivided into record type and arranged chronologically, usually by date of the individual meeting.

CGRL 20/ INTERNATIONAL TEAM

The International Team Files are a small diverse collection of materials which are often a repeat of the International Secretariate Files. (The International Team acts as President of U.S. Grail and distributes international communications from the International Secretariate which accounts for much of the duplication of materials in the two files.) Included in this unit is correspondence, elections, financial reports, a questionnaire, minutes, reports, subject file, structures and miscellaneous material.

The correspondence series consists of letters and memos from the International Team, or individuals on the Team, to members of the U.S. Grail and the International Secretariate. Included also are subseries on "International Staff Exchange" dealing with people coming from overseas to the U.S. and people from the U.S. going overseas; a section on "Leadership" which was an international discussion question and finally a small correspondence file on the International President's (then Simone Tagher) visit to the U.S. A small series on elections is also included, but deals only with the election of the International Team and a large file on the election of the International President under the U.S. process. The Financial Reports series contains the formal budget of the U.S. Grail fund from June-September 1977.

The International Team files also include the typewritten dittoed formal results of a questionnaire sent to different International Teams about the Grail in their country. The results are, perhaps, a better indication of where the Grail was at in that particular country at that particular time rather than an overall history of each country. The minutes series consists of minutes from an International Team Meeting held January 1977. Reports: A series made up of two miscellaneous reports. Subject File: The series contains two publications from the U.S. Grail. Structures: A small series which deals with the U.S. Grail's process of affirming International Structures. Miscellaneous: Contains only a single item, a reprint of an article from the Cincinnati Catholic Telegraph on Simone Tagher's visit in 1976. See International Secretariate and General Financial Records for additional information. All material is arranged chronologically within each series.

CGRL 20/2 International Staff Exchange Correspondence 1975-1978

CGRL 20/ ELECTIONS

The Elections unit is a very small file which contains guidelines, correspondence, announcements, ballots and voting results. A small amount of the material deals with the election of the International President, the International General Assembly delegates, the National Board and the national committee. The bulk of the file covers the 1967 election of U.S. Grail President. The material is arranged by individual elections and then chronologically within each election.

CGRL 20-21/ NATIONAL NUCLEUS

The national nucleus unit is divided into several series: correspondence, meetings, committees, formation files, statistics, documents, financial reports, liturgies, reference files, scrapbooks, retreats, excerpts, forms.

The correspondence series is large and varied. It includes correspondence on: the "Basis for Consultation" mostly an analysis of past Grail policies by nucleus members with suggestions on how they might be improved; the "Draft Statement on the Nucleus," primarily drafts with comments or letters of explanation; a file of correspondence with Grail leaders (e.g. National or International Presidents, National Board). Also included is a very small file dealing with "Last Will and Testament" correspondence which helped set up a standard practice for comparing wills for nucleus members if they desired the Grail's assistance in the matter; and a "Record of Mailing" file, which is simply correspondence with directions on where, in what form, when, and to whom mailings should go. Finally, there is a very small file by the Nucleus Study Group "Wider Horizons." By and large most of the file consists of form letters with the "Basis for Consultation" subseries being the most notable exception. The material is arranged chronologically within subseries.

The meetings series consists of material produced or relating to U.S. or International nucleus meetings. Within each meeting file there are reference files, correspondence and reports about particular meetings.

In most instances the material is filed chronologically within one folder by meeting date. Other meetings have sufficient material to warrant dividing them into record types. The records are arranged chronologically by meeting date and chronologically with each folder or record type.

Committees: This series contains material on specific committees, set up to study a specific issue rather than the broad issue concerns of the general nucleus meetings. The material ranges from correspondence, to reports to suggestions and evaluations. The material is grouped first by committee, then arranged chronologically within each folder.

Formation Files: This series contains transcribed talks, outlines of course, discussions, programs and minutes of meetings held with nucleus members in training. Also included is a file on possible doctors and groups to employ for the psychological testing of prospective nucleus members. Material is arranged chronologically by date of meeting or program and chronologically within each folder.

The Statistics series consists of background information about nucleus members including name, address, education and how long they have been in contact with the Grail. This subseries is divided into national and international members and arranged alphabetically. Other statistics contained in this series are lists of members, dates of dedication, birthdays, occupations, and education to name a few. This information is arranged chronologically by list The final segment of this file includes personal data lists on prospective nucleus candidates. Included are names, addresses, ages, education, work experience, how long they have been in contact with the Grail and qualities that would or would not make them a good nucleus member. The lists, with several different people on them, are arranged chronologically.

Documents: This series contains photocopies of all (pre 1972) signed nucleus members' "solemn promise" upon their dedication to the Grail nucleus. The originals were sent to the International Grail Headquarters. The material is divided into "released" members and present members (as of February 1972), then alphabetically within each group.

Financial Reportsf: This series contains general miscellaneous nucleus financial reports. Also included are individual budgets and estimates of income submitted by each nucleus member. See General Financial Records for more information. The material is arranged chronologically except for the individual budgets which are arranged alphabetically.

Liturgies: A small file consisting largely of Dedication Ceremonies, both the religious service and the informal introductory letters sent out before hand by each candidate. The material is arranged chronologically.

Reference File: An incomplete reference year book file of material sent to U.S. nucleus members from both the National and International Grail. The material is arranged chronologically.

Scrapbook: This series contains a single scrapbook from the Scottish Grail to the first twelve Americans to make their nucleus dedication. Included are drawings, quotes from Scripture and notes of encouragement to each of the twelve new members.

Retreats: A file of scattered schedules and minutes of retreats given for nucleus members at Grailville in 1964. The material is arranged chronologically.

Excerpts: A very small series made up of typed excerpts from talks by Grail members or talks of interest given to nucleus members. The material is arranged chronologically.

Forms: This series contains blank forms used by the Grail to collect general statistical and health information about individual nucleus members The file is arranged alphabetically by type of form.

CGRL 22-29/ NATIONAL MOVEMENT RECORDS

A large inclusive unit of records which are the administrative files of the U.S. Grail movement. Until the late 1960s, Grailville files were also included with this unit. After this point the Grail and Grailville were treated as separate units. The file has been divided into major series of Administration, National Council, National Meetings, Committees, Miscellaneous Teams and Groups, Interest Areas, Special Projects, Aggiornamentao Year, Correspondence, Reports to the International, International, Membership, Statistics / Tests, Finances, History of the Grail, Designs / Symbols, Prayers / Liturgy and the Oral History Project. See individual files and Grailville files for additional information as well as material on other countries and regional files.

Administration: This series primarily consists of material from the late 1960s on. Included are evaluations, correspondence, minutes, agendas, reports, lists, structures, job descriptions, office policy and procedures, organization, office personnel, and miscellaneous material. Most files are incomplete, form letter files with the exception of the "Evaluations" subseries which is a survey of how involved people believed they were with the Grail and was really meant to be a mailing list update. Material arranged chronologically, except for "Evaluations" which are arranged alphabetically.

The National Council series contains, in large part, material on individual meetings such as: minutes, correspondence, agendas and reports. Also included in the series is a small correspondence and miscellaneous file. The material is arranged chronologically by date of meeting and is divided into record types if there is enough material to warrant it. The material is arranged chronologically within record type.

National Meetings: This series is very similar to the national council series in the material it contains, including correspondence, minutes, agendas, reports, evaluations and reference files. The series is divided into years; arranged chronologically around the annual meetings; divided into record types, if enough material is present; and arranged chronologically within each record type.

Committees: This is a large series containing the records of numerous, short-lived or defunct committees. Included in this series are the Executive Committee, National Staff Planning Committee, the Coordinating Committee and Finance Committee to name a few. The records consist of agendas, minutes, correspondence, reports, reference files, resource material, evaluations and miscellaneous materials. The records are grouped by committee and within each committee by record type or subject, then chronologically within each division.

The Teams and Groups unit is actually a number of miscellaneous units developed to investigate problems and areas of ongoing concern to Grail, or to perform an administrative or counseling task for a Grail function. included are the Participation Core Team, Movement Development Team, Continuity Team, Communications Team, Finance Link Team, Professional Group, Married Women's Group, Lateral Sharing Group and other miscellaneous work groups. The material is grouped first by team, group or work group, then by record type or subject and finally either chronologically or alphabetically within each record type or subject.

Many of the subseries in the Interest Area series were actually former councils of the 1950s, for instance, included are the Christian Culture Council, the Family and Community Council, the Drama Council, and the Religious Education Council. Other subseries act more as a subject file of Grail interests at a particular time, for instance, Film Production, PAVLA Project, Racism, and Religious Search Seminars. Within these subseries are reports, agendas, minutes, correspondence, resource material, questionnaires, scrapbooks, talks and other miscellaneous material. The series is first divided into subseries by council, committee or project name and arranged alphabetically. The subseries are further divided into record types and each record type then arranged either chronologically or alphabetically.

Special Projects consist of one-time, experimental or unique programs, sponsored or attended by the Grail or Grail members. Included within this series are such projects as the Akhmim project (a Grail sponsored weaving project in Egypt), Eucharistic Congress, (YWCA) Convocation on Racism, and World Day of Prayer to name a few. See also Courses / Program series for additional information.

Courses / Programs: This series contains examples of courses or programs sponsored by the Grail for Grail members only or for the general public. See the Courses / Programs unit for additional materials. The material is grouped by course / program then divided into record type and arranged chronologically.

Aggiornamento Year: This series is a collection of material relating to the administration of the Grail Aggiornamento process in the mid 1960s. Included are research papers, correspondence, discussion transcripts, guidelines and miscellaneous material. Additional material may be located under other administrative units both national and international. Material arranged chronologically with each record type.

Scrapbooks: Contained in the scrapbook series are numerous publicity scrapbooks, as well as a few incomplete, pseudo reference yearbook files. Material arranged chronologically.

News Clippings: A very small file of news items. Arranged chronologically.

The correspondence series is a collection of correspondence between national Grail leaders and the U.S. Catholic hierarchy. The bulk of the series is general movement mailings. The material is arranged chronologically within the subseries.

Report to the International: Most often reports of progress and problems the U.S. Grail faces. Arranged chronologically.

International: This series is a small collection of the interaction between the International and the U.S. Grail. More substantial information may be obtained from the International Secretariate Unit and specific U.S. Administrative Units. Arranged by record type and chronologically within each type.

Membership: The bulk of this file is an information file on U.S. Grail participants, Americans overseas and friends of the Grail. This information was used as a mailing list update. The material is grouped into "U.S.A. Participation," "Americans Overseas" and "Friends of the Grail" and arranged alphabetically within each group.

Statistics / Lists: General information lists are the major components of this series. Material is divided into list subject and arranged chronologically.

Finances: Material consists of Reports and Budgets for miscellaneous Grail units. Additional information can be found in the General Financial Records and individual unit files. Arranged chronologically.

History of the Grail: A miscellaneous collection of facts about the Grail. Material is divided into subject and arranged chronologically.

Designs / Symbols: Scattered, rough draft drawings of possible Grail logos.

Prayers / Liturgy: A very small collection of miscellaneous prayers or liturgies used by the Grail. Arranged chronologically.

Oral History Project: A single file on the 1982 project of preparing oral histories of the early U.S. Grail members. See "Audio Tapes" for additional information. Material arranged chronologically.

CGRL 30-/ GENERAL FINANCIAL RECORDS

This series consists of annual, quarterly and monthly financial reports of all U.S. Grail units, projects and programs, along with some international material. Also included are agendas and minutes from financial meetings, correspondence, ledgers, check registers and in the regional files, legal documents such as incorporation documents, rental agreements, etc. Of special interest are the regional files which give detailed information on the operations of individual centers and their programs in the late 1950s and early 1960s.

The General Financial Records are divided first into geographic units - International, National, Regional (and alphabetically within this unit by state and center), and Grailville. Within these geographic units the material is further alphabetically divided into individual programs, units, or projects; then by record type and finally, chronologically within each record type.

CGRL 38-46/ REGIONAL FILES

The Regional Files are in many instances a rich, varied and detailed account of the workings of Grail centers and Teams throughout the U.S. The files may be as large as the still existing San Jose or Cornwall-on-Hudson Centers or as small as the Maryland file where only a survey report was made. The material contained is from the Grailville files on individual centers and the centers themselves as they closed or transferred material to Grailville. Included are reports, correspondence, program files, address lists, minutes, agendas, scrapbooks, dramas, scattered financial reports especially from regional bookstores as they closed, scattered newspaper clippings, news releases and miscellaneous material.

Of special interest are the well-documented examples of social projects initiated by the Grail in New York, San Jose and especially Lafayette where the Grail was involved in black voter registration in the early 1960s. Also of interest are the Chicago files which are really reports from Doddridge Farm, and also contains the telegram inviting the Grail to establish itself in the United States.

The material has been divided geographically and arranged alphabetically by state. Within each state the material has been subdivided and arranged alphabetically by city or center. Within these city files the material is divided into record type and then arranged chronologically or alphabetically.

CGRL 47-58/ CORRESPONDENCE

This series contains general correspondence files with persons and groups. The correspondence deals with subjects from the administrative task of arranging for lecture and course speakers to personal views on social problems and issues. Contained are letters from such well known individuals as Dorothy Day and Marshall McLuhan to various bishops and priests. Included also, are a few magazine articles and newspaper clippings about individual correspondents. Single letters of inquiry with no additional follow up have been removed and destroyed.

CGRL 61/ GRAIL BUILDING FUND

A small file composed of material relating mostly to the late 1950s / early 1960s National Grail Building Fund Project. Headed by Janet Kalven, this national fund is separate from the individual centers of Grailville Building Fund, although the line of demarcation is no always clear, especially in the Grailville case.

Most of the file contains correspondence. This correspondence covers such issues as pleas to donors, subsequent thank you letters, suggestions from Grail members on what improvements are needed most, letters to architects and workmen, and information to non-Grail members (both clergy and lay persons) helping to sponsor the drive. There are a few legal documents and scattered reports on various issues from tallies of donations to reports of how the drive is progressing with individual centers and teams. See also Grailville Building Fund unit for additional material.

The material is divided into record type and arranged chronologically within each record type.

CGRL 66-74/ SPECIAL PROJECTS

CGRL 66-68/ SEMESTER AT GRAILVILLE (SAG) 1968-1975

This diverse series contains files from the Semester at Grailville (SAG) program, a self-directed learning program for women, with enrollment of 12-25 students each semester. Students were drawn from different universities throughout the country, and were granted academic credit by their home institutions for participation. Much of the actual program material covers the students' community involvement work and their work in additional interest areas such as poetry, guitar, French, Spanish, pottery, Black history, women's history and others. Other series such as address lists, colleges, conferences, contracts, correspondence, evaluations, flyers, forms, reference year books, reports and resource material are also included.

Address Lists: Concerned with recruiting potential students. The material includes names and addresses of students or others who knew students who might be interested in SAG. This material was used especially in 1975-1976 in an attempt to recruit students. Material arranged chronologically.

Colleges: Files of individual colleges or universities which had students at SAG, were contacted by SAG in an attempt to recruit potential students or were interested in the SAG idea and wanted to learn more about it. Arranged alphabetically by name of school and chronologically within.

Conferences: Contains material from two conferences "Education for Values in the Education of Women" which helped bring bout SAG idea and "Ursuline Academy Community Learning Work" which was held at Grailville and resourced by SAG staff Arranged alphabetically by title of conference.

Contracts: Copies of blank contracts used with universities sending students to SAG. Signed contracts are in with the indivudal college folder. Arranged chronologically.

Correspondence: Correspondence is grouped into general, which contains miscellaneous letters and then into larger groupings either about a specific correspondent or purpose of correspondence. Some groupings include Greater Cincinnati Consortium of Colleges and Universities, letters of inquiry about the SAG program from students and staff. Arranged alphabetically by type and then chronologically within each division.

Evaluations: Are written reports, one written by SAG staff and the other by a person who studied SAG for a graduate course. The reports give reasons why SAG succeeded and why it failed. Arranged chronologically.

Flyers / Brochures: Material sent out to help recruit students or give them additional information about SAG and Grailville once they have been accepted into the program. Arranged chronologically.

Forms: Forms used to keep track of people interested in attending SAG, working at SAG, working with SAG or colleges which were visited. Also included are miscellaneous forms such as applications, travel forms and proposed project forms. Arranged alphabetically by type.

Reference Year Books: A copy of every piece of material, mass produced by office for handout at SAG. Covers SAG #1-4. Arranged chronologically by SAG date and number.

Reports: The final printed report of every SAG program beginning with the initial planning through its final evaluation. Of special interest are the student prepared reports of SAG. Arranged chronologically.

Resource Material: Miscellaneous material in two folders are on self-directed learning and the other containing a "Woman" bibliography prepared by 1974 SAG students. Arranged chronologically.

CGRL 66/1 SAG: ADDRESS LISTS - Recruiting 1971; 1972; 1973; 1974; 1975-1976; n.d.

CGRL 69/ CULTURAL EXCHANGE MEETINGS ON AFRICA

Series contains files of the cultural exchange meetings on Africa (CEMA), whereby 12 African women came to the United States and traveled with three Americans throughout the United States in an attempt to learn about one another's cultures.

Address Lists: Contains addresses of African participants and Americans coming to programs or aiding the process. Arranged chronologically by list.

Correspondence: Broken into categories such as General, with participants and different individuals and groups like Bishop Bernardin and Church Women United. Also included is correspondence dealing specifically with fund raising and letters of recommendation from influential Catholic leaders for the Grail to use in obtaining funds. Material arranged alphabetically by general folder heading and chronologically within.

Evaluations: Written evaluations of different programs held in connection with CEMA. Arranged chronologically.

Financial Needs: Records including check registers from the CEMA account, the CEMA ledger and monthly financial reports on the project as well as Cornwall's financial records in the project. Arranged chronologically.

Liturgical Material: A small collection of material used in celebrations. Arranged chronologically.

Newspaper Clippings: Clippings from different areas where programs participants visited. Arranged chronologically.

Programs: Files on individual programs either directly related to CEMA or attended by the participants. Programs are either regional or topical. Includes correspondence, reports, invitations and evaluations. Material arranged alphabetically by program and chronologically within.

Proposals: Material from original idea of setting up the program. Arranged chronologically.

Publicity: Includes non-newspaper clipping material, including story in St. Anthony Messenger.

Report: Series includes the final report sent to all who donated time or money and persons or organizations involved.

Sample Grail Projects in Africa: African women's projects which they, as Grail members, are running in their own countries. Arranged chronologically.

CGRL 70/ ART AND BOOK PROGRAM

Includes material from department concerned with distribution and production of Grail books and art work including such items as posters, cards and statutes. The department was headed by Janet Kalven until the early 1970s.

Correspondence: A fairly complete series of diverse material covering correspondence with authors and artists producing works, with distributors selling the works and to manufacturers mass producing the work, also contained are some comments from "Readers" reviewing such works as 12 Days of Christmas and Elizabeth Reid's, I Belong Where I'm Needed.

Financial Records: The series is comprised mainly of check registers, although one folder contains scattered reports (annual, quarterly and monthly) on different aspects of the program.

Reports: Written reports of different aspects of operation, in terms of technological aspects, production of artists and problems with distribution and mass production.

Legal Contracts: Most material represented is contracts between distributors and Grail, but also some rights to publish, copyright and transfer of copyright material.

Agendas: Scattered agendas and points of discussion for irregular meetings held about program.

Minutes: Scattered minutes and summaries of meetings held irregularly about problems in program.

Cards: Card designs for different feasts (Easter, Christmas, etc.) and occasions; also phoenix cards, variations of one theme, the phoenix arising from the flames, including some original rough drafts.

Catalogue: Different catalogues, produced by Grail, illustrating Grail material for sale. The 1972 catalogue is the "Christian family Catalogue" which is not Grail related but features Grail items. Also included are the rough drafts of catalogues as designed by Grail artists.

Publicity Files: Files on two better known Grail artists, artist Trina Paulus and writer Elizabeth Reid. Primarily a biography and listing of past awards.

Designs: Two folders of different prayers, primarily meal time, at different times throughout the church year, contained in decorative folders. Also one item of vestment design with cloth swatch.

CGRL 71-74/ COURSES AND PROGRAMS 1941-1973

Contains material on courses held at Grailville, both those sponsored by the Grail and those which other groups sponsored but held at Grailville. Also included are a few courses which were not held at Grailville but were attended by Grailville denizens or given by Grail members at other locations. Included are course outlines, syllabi, flyers, brochures, announcements, prayer material, financial records, correspondence and other material dealing with programs. The files cover such courses as early summer courses, year school courses, Oriental Institute. The file is a good example of the types of issues the Grail was concerned with as represented by the subject of the course and the speakers they sponsored. Material is arranged chronologically by year then within each alphabetically by title of course, then chronologically within the folders.

CGRL PUBLICATIONS, TALKS, AND LECTURES

CGRL A1-A3/ FLYERS

Flyers, brochures, programs and miscellaneous publications which are neither newsletters, periodicals, bulletins nor books. Also included are catalogues and flyers from Grail bookstores, as well as school catalogues, cards (Christmas, Easter, Engagement, postcards, etc.) and reprints of articles often used as publicity flyers or educational flyers about the movement.

The material is arranged first by the following publisher / author units: International Secretariate, other countries, U.S.-national material, Grailville, regional. Within each publisher / author unit the material is arranged alphabetically by country, state, region or city and then chronologically within. (Although the International Secretariate published the same material in different languages for different countries, the material is filed in the International Secretariate section.)

CGRL A4/ NEWSPAPER CLIPPINGS

This series consists of miscellaneous clippings about Grail activity, both internationally and nationally. Although the bulk of the material concerns the U.S. Grail there are individual files on countries, Grailville and center or state files. The clippings are as complex as an article or series of articles written by or about Grail members and their work or as simple as an advertisement for a Grail course or lecture. For additional information see individual country or center files and flyers.

Newspaper clippings are arranged by country and then within by state, city, or center if there is sufficient material to warrant it. The clippings are arranged chronologically within each geographic division.

CGRL BOOKS

This series contains books written by, for, about or relating closely to the Grail. The books contained in the miscellaneous section were not written, nor published by the Grail, but were used by the Grail either for general information or training purposes. The books are in French, Spanish, Portuguese, German, Dutch and English.

The material is grouped by the following author / publishing units: van Ginneken, International Secretariate, other countries, U.S. (Grailville and regional) and miscellaneous within each of the above author / publishing units. The books are arranged alphabetically by author and within each author, alphabetically by title.

CGRL 75-79/ PERIODICALS

Newsletters, bulletins, etc. A large diverse series consisting of materials written by or for Grail members. The material comes from various sources, such as the International Secretariate or a High School Grail group in the U.S. The information contained is news of Movement members, general Movement news or material intended to be used as educational material giving summaries, bibliographies or book reviews of material relevant to Grail concerns. This series is a very good, general information source on the Grail and its individual members. The material is written in French, Spanish, Portuguese, German, Dutch and English according to the country of origin.

The series is first divided into the following units: International, other countries and U.S. (General, council or group, and regional) according to place of origin. The material is arranged alphabetically by individual groups within the larger geographic division, then alphabetically by the name of the newsletter, periodical or bulletin and chronologically within each newsletter, periodical or bulletin. Name changes are shown in parenthesis, with the most recent name first.

CGRL 81-82/ DRAMAS

Contains scripts of plays, readings, stories and films produced or used in part by the Grail, including some original plays written by Grail members. Also included are numerous revisions and stage directions for productions. Of special interest is a signature of Fr. Daniel Berrigan on his play, "The Springs of Silence." There is one folder at the end of the series marked miscellaneous which contains lists of plays with evaluations and recommendations about their feasibility for Grail use. Dramas are arranged alphabetically by title of play.

CGRL 83-85/ TALKS AND LECTURES

Transcripts of talks, lectures, notes from talks, articles (as read to Grail members), book reviews, as well as papers written for courses both at Grail training centers and for other schools. The talks and lectures were given to Grail members only or were open to one general public. Also included are transcripts or outlines of speeches, talks or lectures which Grail members attended at other places and reported back to the Grail.

The material is divided into Grail and non-Grail members then arranged alphabetically by speaker name and chronologically within each speakers' collection.

CGRL 86/ CATECHETICS AND ECUMENISM

A subject file on catechetics and ecumenism. This series contains magazine articles, newspaper clippings, talks, lectures, lesson plans and reports on different aspects of catechetics and ecumenism. Material is filed under name of well-known catechetic instructor or writer or under a general term or area of ecumenism. The series includes such files as those on Rev. Josef Goldbrunner, Rev. P. Babin, and a file on the Christian unity question of the late 1950s, early 1960s. The material is arranged alphabetically by subject or name and chronologically within each folder.

CGRL 325/59 KERYGMA

AGRL The Grail : Audio-Visual Material

AUDIO TAPES. Recordings of lectures, courses, meetings, conferences, musical presentations, or religious liturgies. Included are tapes of both Grail and non-Grail members, both religious and lay persons. This is an incomplete collection with large gaps and missing tapes.

FILMS. Films made by or about the Grail or in some instances about areas of interest to the Grail, e.g. "Works of Peace" and "Refugee Camp at Junk Bay, Hong Kong".

VIDEO TAPES. Some video tapes are duplicates of the film series. Additional videos cover interviews with international Grail people, selected program excerpts, workshops, etc.

DGRL The Grail : Digital Data

DGRL +45 5 Boxes of Diskettes

GGRL The Grail : Graphics

SCRAPBOOKS. Photo scrapbooks of events, countries or people; memorabilia scrapbooks on events, such as Lydwine van Kersbergen's 1950s survey trip to Africa; and scrapbooks meant for publicity use and containing pictures, flyers, letters, reports and various other material.

PRINTS. Color and black and white photographs of people, places, events and Grail art work relating to the Grail nationally and internationally. See the Photograph card catalogue or "Photograph Log" for specific information on location.

SLIDES. Color slides of people, places, events and Grail art works relating to the Grail both nationally and internationally. See "Slide Log" for more specific information on location.

The inventory below relies heavily on packing lists sent by The Grail. The collection has not yet been fully processed.
